{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5df83860-c7af-4ddf-834d-e994710d5bfb","content":"You're on MSTest 3.8.2 which supports constructor injection for `TestContext`. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    // Constructor injection for TestContext (MSTest v3+)\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous initialization here\n    }\n\n    // Async initialization (runs before each test)\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // Async setup work (e.g., seed database, start services)\n        await SomeAsyncSetup();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task MyTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Test is running\");\n        // ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **Constructor** — receives `TestContext` via DI; use for sync setup and storing references.\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — use for `async` initialization that can't go in the constructor.\n- **`[ClassInitialize]`** — for one-time async setup shared across all tests in the class (static method).\n\nThis avoids the older `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern, which is still supported but less idiomatic in MSTest v3+.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9b00d7ef-459a-4928-bc4d-017db25d1650","outputTokens":329,"requestId":"E3C6:182BD0:18324EF:1B16C13:6A0528A5"},"id":"745149a1-83ed-4c2d-a679-cb6d9aa56481","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:43:09.717Z","parentId":"6bc1ec00-0dc0-4a1b-a2a5-72a6db48db36"}
